<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="description">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,253,1325]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,563,505,533]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Description of 3 
<superScript attach="left" box="[392,407,505,519]" fontSize="6" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">rd</superScript>
instar larva.
</emphasis>
Size (based on 
<specimenCount box="[747,892,508,533]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="generic">7 specimens</specimenCount>
): BL 
<quantity box="[956,1075,508,533]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.025" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="10.25">10.25 mm</quantity>
; HL 
<quantity box="[1133,1235,508,533]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.35" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="2.35">2.35 mm</quantity>
(2.07â€“2.41), HW 
<quantity box="[151,256,544,569]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="1.75" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="1.75">1.75 mm</quantity>
(1.60â€“2.05), ML 
<quantity box="[470,575,544,569]" metricMagnitude="-3" metricUnit="m" metricValue="2.16" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="mm" value="2.16">2.16 mm</quantity>
(2.07â€“2.28), HW/HL 0.74, ML/HL 0.92. General colouring light brown, mottled with dark, ventral side pale with a dark pattern; head capsule with extensive dorsal dark markings, ocular tubercles black, ventral side of the head pale with the exception of dark markings surrounding the gula; mandibles reddish brown; legs pale; setae of the body black. Head longer than wide; anterior margin of the clypeo-labrum covered by black dolichasters (
<figureCitation box="[500,598,688,713]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[218,1349,207,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-47@36.[209,1361,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18. Megistopus flavicornis (Rossi, 1790), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; aâ€“g: diagnostic characters, see species description. (photo by C. Cesaroni)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909429" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909429/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18b</figureCitation>
); mandibles as long as the head capsule (
<figureCitation box="[1063,1159,688,713]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[218,1349,207,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-47@36.[209,1361,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18. Megistopus flavicornis (Rossi, 1790), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; aâ€“g: diagnostic characters, see species description. (photo by C. Cesaroni)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909429" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909429/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18a</figureCitation>
); interdental mandibular setae: (3â€“4)(1)(1)(0); labial palpi covered by black dolichasters (
<figureCitation box="[870,963,724,749]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[218,1349,207,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-47@36.[209,1361,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18. Megistopus flavicornis (Rossi, 1790), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; aâ€“g: diagnostic characters, see species description. (photo by C. Cesaroni)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909429" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909429/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18f</figureCitation>
). Pronotum thickly covered by black setae (
<figureCitation box="[159,258,760,785]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[218,1349,207,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-47@36.[209,1361,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18. Megistopus flavicornis (Rossi, 1790), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; aâ€“g: diagnostic characters, see species description. (photo by C. Cesaroni)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909429" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909429/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18d</figureCitation>
); mesothoracic spiracles raised on over-developed tubercles, considerably longer than the mesothoracic setiferous processes (
<figureCitation box="[390,487,796,821]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[218,1349,207,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-47@36.[209,1361,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18. Megistopus flavicornis (Rossi, 1790), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; aâ€“g: diagnostic characters, see species description. (photo by C. Cesaroni)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909429" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909429/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18c</figureCitation>
); thoracic setiferous processes pedunculated. Abdominal spiracles pedunculated and prominent, clearly visible from above (
<figureCitation box="[628,731,832,857]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[218,1349,207,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-47@36.[209,1361,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18. Megistopus flavicornis (Rossi, 1790), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; aâ€“g: diagnostic characters, see species description. (photo by C. Cesaroni)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909429" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909429/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Fig. 18e</figureCitation>
); VIII abdominal sternite provided with reduced odontoid processes; IX sternite pale, without conspicuous lateral markings, rastra with the internal pair of setae less than a quarter of the others in size (
<figureCitation box="[472,570,904,929]" captionStart="FIGURE 18" captionStartId="36.[151,249,1973,1995]" captionTargetBox="[218,1349,207,1924]" captionTargetId="figure-47@36.[209,1361,193,1931]" captionTargetPageId="36" captionText="FIGURE 18. Megistopus flavicornis (Rossi, 1790), 3rd instar larva (Italy: Sardinia, Alghero). Dorsal (above), ventral (middle) and lateral (below) view; aâ€“g: diagnostic characters, see species description. (photo by C. Cesaroni)." figureDoi="http://doi.org/10.5281/zenodo.4909429" httpUri="https://zenodo.org/record/4909429/files/figure.png" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
Fig. 
<quantity box="[524,570,904,929]" metricMagnitude="-2" metricUnit="kg" metricValue="1.8" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" unit="g" value="18.0">18g</quantity>
</figureCitation>
).
</paragraph>
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,253,1325]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,343,940,965]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Bio-ecology.</emphasis>
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rossi" baseAuthorityYear="1790" box="[351,509,940,965]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Megistopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">
<emphasis box="[351,509,940,965]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">M. flavicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
is a relatively euryoecious species, reported for Mediterranean-like environments characterized by the presence of sand-like substratum such as coastal dunes, internal sandy deposits and river banks. The larvae are usually found in shaded conditions such as at the base of trees or in proximity of other shelters.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="distribution">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,253,1325]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,352,1084,1109]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Distribution.</emphasis>
Widespread in the Mediterranean basin, reaching 
<collectingCountry box="[925,1007,1084,1109]" name="Austria" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Austria</collectingCountry>
and 
<collectingCountry box="[1065,1163,1084,1108]" name="Hungary" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Hungary</collectingCountry>
in the north and 
<collectingCountry box="[1361,1406,1084,1107]" name="Iran" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Iran</collectingCountry>
in the east.
</paragraph>
</subSubSection>
<subSubSection pageId="35" pageNumber="36" type="discussion">
<paragraph blockId="35.[151,1436,253,1325]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">
<emphasis bold="true" box="[199,315,1156,1181]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Remarks.</emphasis>
This antlion is distinguished by extremely developed spiracles, an unusual and rare character in the whole family 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Latreille" authorityYear="1802" box="[313,501,1192,1217]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="family">Myrmeleontidae</taxonomicName>
, therefore considered worth of generic value by 
<bibRefCitation author="Stange, L. A." box="[1069,1233,1192,1217]" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" pagination="1 - 565" refId="ref42121" refString="Stange, L. A. (2004) A systematic catalog, bibliography and classification of the world antlions (Insecta: Neuroptera: Myrmeleontidae). Memoirs of the American Entomological Institute, 74, 1 - 565." type="journal article" year="2004">Stange (2004)</bibRefCitation>
. Nevertheless the discovery of the larva of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Navas" baseAuthorityYear="1912" box="[457,567,1228,1253]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Megistopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="lucasi">
<emphasis box="[457,567,1228,1253]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">M. lucasi</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
, in which these structures are not overdeveloped, allows to consider this character as exclusive of 
<taxonomicName baseAuthorityName="Rossi" baseAuthorityYear="1790" box="[446,606,1264,1289]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Megistopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="species" species="flavicornis">
<emphasis box="[446,606,1264,1289]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">M. flavicornis</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
. Therefore, the larvae of the genus 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Rambur" authorityYear="1842" box="[1026,1155,1265,1288]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Megistopus" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[1026,1155,1265,1288]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Megistopus</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
differs from the closely related 
<taxonomicName authorityName="Schneider" authorityYear="1845" box="[234,396,1300,1323]" class="Insecta" family="Myrmeleontidae" genus="Gymnocnemia" kingdom="Animalia" order="Neuroptera" pageId="35" pageNumber="36" phylum="Arthropoda" rank="genus">
<emphasis box="[234,396,1300,1323]" italics="true" pageId="35" pageNumber="36">Gymnocnemia</emphasis>
</taxonomicName>
only in details of the mandibles and of the abdominal IX sternite.
</paragraph>
